We came to university to understand the world. But all we want to do now is change it. Of course, my immediate environments have been mission critical and folks deserve recognizing. (Before I get flamed, there will be more posts) Thus -

To my enthusiastic academic comrades ("survivors") who forwarded me elaborate answers to homeworks and distilled a semester's worth of learning in a night every semester, ELI5-ed. Know that you are legendary and fellows of much Character.

To the stylo Architecture students with their chinos and 'kicks' who, once in a blue moon, emerged from their cave for fruit and fresh air. One day I shall find out where you buy the damn shoes to complete the aesthetic.

To the ladies in and around school who were deprived of time with me. Sympathies aplenty.

To these lads in this photo and more who I was blessed to have known. It would be unjust to say you all changed my life - I didn't have much before that to begin with. Our struggles and conversation taught me more than what the entirety of formal schooling could. Anything I do in this world will always trace back its origins to you, your name in shining lights. (c u @ 55 in 5 minutes.) I learned much from you all to value the finer things as much as the budget meals with steamed rice and a crushed pack of chips. All tangible. All filling. Yum.

The true tangibles are, of course, the stories. Forever. Many, many but not safe for social media. Suffice to say it was all worth it. How I see the world has changed and I required it.

All of us (those in the photo and in subsequent ones) came to university to learn. What we didn't know was that this learning isn't so much academic as it is personal. To look within, to know that deception wasn't symptomatic of a wider audience but rather stemmed from inside. It was an exercise in knowing what is the point of Agrim Singh (or <insert name here>) on this planet. What is the point of whatever's on around. 
And, I would think, we found the answer, and now owe it to ourselves to pay this off through who we are. Our thoughts, our emotions, our naughty jokes.

Thank you all. Make it count.

I am very liberal with the idea of "home". That is, any place that I find remote emotional comfort in gets to be called as such. This is also why we put up posters and things of personal comfort to aid the process.
That also means that I suck at dealing with moving out. Ever since I've started living on my own I've struggled with "leaving" - to pack up and truly move base. It gets worse with tangibles that hold memories aplenty. That pinboard was a host to ticket stubs, photos, letters that friends wrote in good and bad times. As a serial hoarder it gets worse when you're trying to truly let go of things while packing up (I had to take a moment to truly convince myself to get rid of a T-shirt that has served me well for 8 years.)
But the room is more than tangibles. It is a sanctuary that I had to myself in Singapore. It was the place where I spent hours working with friends on "the next big thing", stressing over school that no one got to see, weeping over relationships that could have been; it was a fortress of solitude. 
What I'm trying to get at is that I've had a rather torrid time getting to wrap up a few years worth of my life in a space of 20 hours. Besides discovering things that had gotten buried with time, including Christmas cards from @pinkpavzzzzz and @strawhearts that I finally read 8 months too late (üòû), I found an answer to the question that defines school - that I had a Good time @sutdsg and given another chance I'd be here all over again with the people who made it what it was. 
A new phase is imminent and I look forward to it.

I'm not a big fan of the holidays, especially Christmas. It becomes difficult, I guess, when everyone from the school/uni goes back, the locals are back with their families, one's away from home for the festive seasons and increasingly spend holiday time being homesick or wondering if I'm truly all alone. I'm not Scrooge, though. What gets me through the season is the positivity, the unconditional love for those around you, even people whom you may or may not know, and that's the only reason I like Christmas. It's a time to reflect on the year, to cherish new friends made and to appreciate those who decide to give without expecting much in return.

Thank you to those whom I've had the pleasure of having around me, in good times and bad. I appreciate it all and am truly grateful for everything. I hope ice managed to enrich your lives in some small way as well. Here's to a merry Christmas and a pleasant year ahead. We'll all survive :)
